WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.100
I think this is an exciting trial, at least in the Waldenstrom's world, because this is a treatment that we've seen so far that can potentially overcome some of the mutations that occur in Waldenstrom.

00:00:12.100 --> 00:00:33.560
So, as I mentioned briefly yesterday, patients can have CXCR4 mutations or develop TP53 mutations, and with our standard therapies with BTK inhibitors and venetoclax, often the impact of those therapies can be different, or the therapy efficacy can be different depending on those mutations.

00:00:34.280 --> 00:00:38.820
So, Lankas, Texamab, Tesserine, it's a CD19 antibody drug conjugate.

00:00:39.740 --> 00:00:41.860
It is FDA approved and refrigerated.

00:00:42.100 --> 00:00:52.760
It's directed at a large B-cell lymphoma, but we thought it was a good agent to be using in Waldenstrom's because there are no prior data with CD19-targeted therapies in Waldenstrom's.

00:00:53.160 --> 00:01:03.460
But the lymphocytes in Waldenstrom's that we see in the bone marrow are CD19-positive, typically, and also the plasma cell component of Waldenstrom's is typically CD19-positive.

00:01:04.060 --> 00:01:06.040
So, we thought we would pursue this trial.

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:11.260
You can see the statistical information below, but we're aiming for a sample size of 20 patients.

00:01:12.020 --> 00:01:12.080
And...

00:01:12.100 --> 00:01:19.920
And the null hypothesis would be rejected if at least six patients achieved a VGPR, which you'll see in the coming slides, that we did meet the endpoint of this trial.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:23.320
And we saw much deeper responses than we actually expected to see.

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:30.820
This is data on the first 14 valuable patients, although I'll update you now because we haven't enrolled the 20 patients.

